{{short description|A system of government which is run by the worst, least qualified, or most unscrupulous citizens}}
{{Wiktionary}}
A '''kakistocracy''' ({{IPAc-en|Àå|k|√¶|k|…™|s|Àà|t|…í|k|…π|…ô|s|i|,_|-|Àà|s|t|…í|k|-}}) is a system of government which is run by the worst, least qualified, or most unscrupulous citizens.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lewitt|first1=Michael|title=Investing In A Kakistocracy|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaellewitt/2016/10/13/investing-in-a-kakistocracy/#216ff3d479c1|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=Forbes|date=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref name="fiske">{{cite book|last1=Fiske|first1=Robert Hartwell|title=The Best Words|date=2011|publisher=Marion Street Press|isbn=9781933338828|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=az5IE6Tu8OkC&pg=PA71|accessdate=21 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> The word was coined as early as the seventeenth century.<ref name="mw2962017">{{cite news|title=Trending: When Government Is Just The Worst|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/news-trend-watch/when-government-is-just-the-worst-20170629|accessdate=22 August 2017|work=Merriam Webster|date=29 June 2017|language=en}}</ref> It also was used by English author [[Thomas Love Peacock]] in 1829, but gained significant use in the first decades of the twenty-first century to criticize populist governments emerging in different democracies around the world.

==Etymology==
The word is derived from two Greek words, ''kakistos'' ({{lang|grc|Œ∫Œ¨Œ∫ŒπœÉœÑŒøœÇ}}; worst) and ''kratos'' ({{lang|grc|Œ∫œÅŒ¨œÑŒøœÇ}}; rule), with a literal meaning of government by the worst people.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Rod L|title=Thingamajigs and Whatchamacallits: Unfamiliar Terms for Familiar Things|date=2011|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9781101515921|page=87|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8hWqD8iG0n4C&pg=PT87|accessdate=21 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> Linguistic equivalents of the English word ''kakistocracy'' are as follows:  its Greek equivalent is ''kakistokratia'' ({{lang|grc|Œ∫Œ±Œ∫ŒπœÉœÑŒøŒ∫œÅŒ±œÑŒØŒ±}}), Catalan ''caquistocr√†cia'', Spanish ''kakistocracia'', French ''kakistocratie'', German ''Kakistokratie'', and Russian ''kakistokratiya'' ({{lang|ru|–∫–∞–∫–∏—Å—Ç–æ–∫—Ä–∞—Ç–∏—è}}).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Charalambidis|first1=Michalis|title=ŒúŒπŒ± Œ¨ŒªŒªŒ∑ ŒïŒªŒªŒ¨Œ¥Œ± ŒºœÄŒøœÅŒµŒØ ŒΩŒ± Œ±ŒΩŒøŒØŒæŒµŒπ œÑŒ∑ œÉœÖŒ∂ŒÆœÑŒ∑œÉŒ∑ Œ≥ŒπŒ± œÑŒ∑ŒΩ ŒïœÖœÅœéœÄŒ∑|url=http://www.tovima.gr/opinions/article/?aid=478892|accessdate=8 December 2016|work=Tovima|date=11 October 2012|language=el}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Froelich|first1=Thomas J.|title=An√†lisi no tan breu de l'estat actual de l'√®tica de la informaci√≥: √®tica de la ignor√†ncia, informaci√≥ incompleta, falsa i falsejada i altres formes d'engany i incompet√®ncia|url=http://bid.ub.edu/39/froehlich.htm|accessdate=4 May 2018|language=ca, en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dimopoulos|first1=Carlos|title=La kakistocracia: El gobierno de los peores - El Impulso|url=http://www.elimpulso.com/apartado-de-lectores/la-kakistocracia-el-gobierno-de-los-peores|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=El Impulso|date=10 August 2013|language=es-es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavoie|first1=Gilbert|title=¬ª La coalition de Legault restera "caquiste"|url=http://blogues.lapresse.ca/gilbertlavoie/2011/11/01/la-coalition-de-legault-restera-%C2%ABcaquiste%C2%BB/|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=Blogues de La Presse|date=1 November 2011|language=fr-CA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=–ö–∞–∫–∏—Å—Ç–æ–∫—Ä–∞—Ç–∏—è –ø–µ—Ä–µ—Ö–æ–¥–Ω–æ–≥–æ –ø–µ—Ä–∏–æ–¥–∞|url=http://politikan.com.ua/2/12/0/17150.htm|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=Politikan|date=7 May 2010}}</ref>

==History==

The earliest use of the word dates to the seventeenth century, in Paul Gosnold's ''A sermon Preached at the Publique Fast the ninth day of Aug. 1644 at St. Maries:''<ref name="mw2962017"/><blockquote>"Therefore we need not make any scruple of praying against such: against those Sanctimonious Incendiaries, who have fetched fire from heaven to set their Country in combustion, have pretended Religion to raise and maintaine a most wicked rebellion: against those Nero's, who have ripped up the wombe of the mother that bare them, and wounded the breasts that gave them sucke: against those Cannibal's who feed upon the flesh and are drunke with the bloud of their own brethren: against those Catiline's who seeke their private ends in the publicke disturbance, and have set the Kingdome on fire to rost their owne egges: against those tempests of the State, those restlesse spirits who can no longer live, then be stickling and medling; who are stung with a perpetuall itch of changing and innovating, transforming our old Hierarchy into a new Presbytery, and this againe into a newer Independency; and our well-temperd Monarchy into a mad kinde of Kakistocracy. Good Lord!"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gosnold|first1=Paul|title=A sermon preached at the publique fast the ninth day of Aug. 1644 at St. Maries, Oxford, before the honorable members of the two Houses of Parliament there assembled by Paul Gosnold ... ; and published by authority. |url=http://tei.it.ox.ac.uk/tcp/Texts-HTML/free/A41/A41582.html|publisher=University of Oxford Text Archive|accessdate=22 August 2017|language=en|date=1644}}</ref></blockquote>

English author [[Thomas Love Peacock]] later used the term in his 1829 novel ''[[The Misfortunes of Elphin]]'', in which he explains kakistocracy represents the opposite of [[aristocracy]], as  ''aristos'' (·ºÑœÅŒπœÉœÑŒøœÇ) means "excellent" in Greek.<ref name="dict">{{cite web|title=Kakistocracy|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/kakistocracy|publisher=Dictionary.com}}</ref> In his 1838 ''Memoir on Slavery'' (which he supported), U.S. Senator [[William Harper (South Carolina)|William Harper]] compared kakistocracy to [[anarchy]], and said it had seldom occurred:<ref name="harper">{{cite book|last1=Harper|first1=William|title=Memoir on Slavery: Read Before the Society for the Advancement of Learning, of South Carolina, at its annual meeting at Columbia, 1837|date=1838|publisher=J. S. Burges|page=49|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-hZWAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA49|accessdate=27 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>

{{quote|Anarchy is not so much the absence of government as the government of the worst‚Äînot aristocracy but kakistocracy‚Äîa state of things, which to the honor of our nature, has seldom obtained amongst men, and which perhaps was only fully exemplified during the worst times of the [[French revolution]], when that horrid hell burnt with its most horrid flame. In such a state of things, to be accused is to be condemned‚Äîto protect the innocent is to be guilty; and what perhaps is the worst effect, even men of better nature, to whom their own deeds are abhorrent, are goaded by terror to be forward and emulous in deeds of guilt and violence.}}

American poet [[James Russell Lowell]] used the term in 1876, in a letter to [[Joel Benton]], writing, "What fills me with doubt and dismay is the degradation of the moral tone. Is it or is it not a result of Democracy? Is ours a 'government of the people by the people for the people,' or a Kakistocracy rather, for the benefit of knaves at the cost of fools?"<ref name="fiske" />

==Usage==
{{Forms of government}}
Use of the word was rare in the early part of the 20th century, but it regained popularity in 1981 with criticism of the [[Reagan administration]]. Since then it has been employed to negatively describe various governments around the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=Let's dump this kakistocracy for good |url=http://www.iol.co.za/sundayindependent/lets-dump-this-kakistocracy-for-good-2084926|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=Sunday Independent|date=30 October 2016}}</ref> It was frequently used by conservative commentator [[Glenn Beck]] to describe the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ali|first=Amro|title=Kakistocracy: a word we need to revive|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/arab-awakening/amro-ali/kakistocracy-word-we-need-to-revive|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=openDemocracy|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>

The word returned to use during the [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 U.S. presidential campaign]], particularly by opponents and critics of Republican presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cay Johnston|first1=David|title=Kakistocracy|url=http://www.nationalmemo.com/kakistocracy/|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=[[The National Memo]]|date=12 February 2016}}</ref>

In May 2016, academic and blogger Amro Ali{{who|date=May 2018}} argued that kakistocracy was a word that needed to be revived.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ali|first1=Amro|title=Kakistocracy: A word we need to revive|url=http://amroali.com/2016/05/kakistocracy-rule-by-the-stupid-unqualified/|website=amroali.com|date=May 9, 2016}}</ref>''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' would later credit Ali's blog post with initiating a wider conversation on the term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2016/12/17/degeneration-nation-it-takes-a-village-of-idiots-to-raise-a-kakistocracy-like-donald-trumps/|title=Degeneration nation: It takes a village of idiots to raise a kakistocracy like Donald Trump‚Äôs|last=McClennen|first=Sophia A.|website=Salon|access-date=2017-01-15}}</ref>

In August 2016, Dan Leger of the [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] newspaper ''[[The Chronicle Herald]]'' suggested that a Trump victory in the U.S. presidential election would require renewed use of the term "kakistocracy."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Leger|first1=Dan|title=LEGER: Trump‚Äôs America would be a 'kakistocracy, ruled by most corrupt or incompetent|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/opinion/1390469-leger-trump%E2%80%99s-america-would-be-a-%E2%80%98kakistocracy%E2%80%99-ruled-by-most-corrupt-or-incompetent|work=[[The Chronicle Herald]]|date=21 August 2016}}</ref>

Since November 2016, the word has been used to describe the Trump administration by critics of that administration on multiple occasions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bouie|first1=Jamelle|title=Government by the Worst Men| url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2016/11/donald_trump_is_bringing_america_government_by_the_worst_men.html|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=Slate|date=18 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Del Signore|first1=John|title=Stay Tuned For Trump's Reality Show 'American Kakistocracy'|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/11/17/will_america_fire_itself.php|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=Gothamist|date=17 November 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120114818/http://gothamist.com/2016/11/17/will_america_fire_itself.php|archivedate=20 November 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marsden|first1=Harriet|title=Kakistocracy may just be the perfect word to describe the Trump government|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/donald-trump-us-president-new-government-white-house-kakistocracy-7422706|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=The Independent|date=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lizza|first1=Ryan|title=Donald Trump's First, Alarming Week as President-Elect|url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/donald-trumps-first-alarming-week-as-president-elect|accessdate=21 November 2016|work=The New Yorker|date=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/03/opinion/sunday/the-trump-tweets-i-want-to-read.html|title=The Trump Tweets I Want to Read|last=Mandvi|first=Aasif|date=2016-12-03|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolf|first1=Stephen|title=Trump's presidency is shaping up to be a kakistocracy: government by the worst possible people|url=http://www.dailykos.com/stories/2016/11/25/1602547/-Trump-s-presidency-is-shaping-up-to-be-a-kakistocracy-government-by-the-worst-possible-people|accessdate=27 November 2016|work=Daily Kos|date=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Krugman|first1=Paul|title=With All Due Disrespect|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/16/opinion/with-all-due-disrespect.html|accessdate=19 January 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=16 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hasan|first1=Mehdi|title=Donald Trump ushers in a new era of kakistocracy: government by the worst people|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/world/2017/01/donald-trump-ushers-new-era-kakistocracy-government-worst-people|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=[[The New Statesman]]|date=20 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ornstein|first1=Norm|title=There's a Word for the State of American Democracy: Kakistocracy|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/10/american-kakistocracy/542391/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=johnbrennan|author=John Brennan|number=984803286006951936|date=13 April 2018|title=Your kakistocracy is collapsing after its lamentable journey. As the greatest Nation history has known, we have the opportunity to emerge from this nightmare stronger & more committed to ensuring a better life for all Americans, including those you have so tragically deceived.|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>

On 29 June 2017, ''[[Merriam-Webster]]'' reported that searches for the word on its online dictionary had spiked to an all-time high that day.<ref name="mw2962017"/> ''The Washington Post'' reported on the use of the word going viral to describe the Trump administration on 13 April 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Selk |first1=Avi |title=Kakistocracy, a 374-year-old word that means ‚Äògovernment by the worst,‚Äô just broke the dictionary |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2018/04/13/kakistocracy-a-374-year-old-word-that-means-government-by-the-worst-just-broke-the-dictionary/ |accessdate=21 November 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=13 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

