====Phonetic realization====
* The close and mid vowels are typically peripheral, but they can at times be somewhat centralized.{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|pp=93‚Äì95}}
* {{IPA|/i, iÀê, u, uÀê/}} are typically near-close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|iÃû}}, {{IPA link|iÃûÀê}}, {{IPA link|uÃû}}, {{IPA link|uÃûÀê}}]}}, but sometimes they can be close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|iÀê}}, {{IPA link|u}}, {{IPA link|uÀê}}]}} instead.{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|pp=93, 95}}
* {{IPA|/…õ, …õÀê, …î, …îÀê/}} are typically mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|…õÃù}}, {{IPA link|…õÃùÀê}}, {{IPA link|…îÃù}}, {{IPA link|…îÃùÀê}}]}}. {{IPA|/…õ, …õÀê/}} are slightly higher than {{IPA|/…î, …îÀê/}} - this can be transcribed in narrow transcription as {{IPA|[{{IPA link|eÃû}}, {{IPA link|eÃûÀê}}]}} vs. {{IPA|[{{IPA link|…îÃù}}, {{IPA link|…îÃùÀê}}]}}. At times, {{IPA|/…õ, …õÀê/}} can be as close as close-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e}}, {{IPA link|eÀê}}]}} and {{IPA|/…î, …îÀê/}} as open as open-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|…î}}, {{IPA link|…îÀê}}]}}.{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|pp=94‚Äì95}}
* Speakers often fail at attempts to pronounce {{IPA|/√¶/}}, pronouncing a vowel that is phonetically too close to either {{IPA|/…õ/}} or {{IPA|/a/}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=55}}
* {{IPA|/a, aÀê/}} are typically open central {{IPA|[{{IPA link|√§}}, {{IPA link|√§Àê}}]}}, but at times they can be somewhat fronted {{IPA|[{{IPA link|a|aÃ†}}, {{IPA link|a|aÃ†Àê}}]}}, retracted {{IPA|[{{IPA link|…ë|…ëÃü}}, {{IPA link|…ë|…ëÃüÀê}}]}} or raised {{IPA|[{{IPA link|…ê}}, {{IPA link|…êÀê}}]}}.{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|pp=94‚Äì95}}
* Under Hungarian influence, some speakers realize {{IPA|/…õÀê, …îÀê/}} as close-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|eÀê}}, {{IPA link|oÀê}}]}} and {{IPA|/a/}} as open back rounded {{IPAblink|…í}}. The close-mid realizations of {{IPA|/…õÀê, …îÀê/}} occur also in southern dialects spoken near the river [[Ipeƒæ]].{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=54, 92}}

====Other notes====
* Vowel length is not phonemic in Eastern dialects,{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=375}} which have only five vowel phonemes ({{IPA|/i, u, …õ, …î, a/}}, some speakers also have {{IPA|/√¶/}}).
* In Western dialects, vowels that are short due to the rhythmical rule{{Explain|date=September 2018}} are often realized as long, and thus violating the rule.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=376}}
* {{IPA|/y, yÀê, ≈ì, ≈ìÀê, …îÀê/}} occur only in loanwords.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=375}}{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=64‚Äì65}} Just as other mid vowels, {{IPA|/≈ì, ≈ìÀê/}} are phonetically true-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|≈ìÃù}}, {{IPA link|≈ìÃùÀê}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=64}} Among these vowels, only {{IPA|/…îÀê/}} is consistently realized in the correct manner, whereas the occurrence of the front rounded vowels {{IPA|/y, yÀê, ≈ì, ≈ìÀê/}} has been reported only by {{Harvcoltxt|Kr√°ƒæ|1988}}, who states that the front rounded vowels appear only in the high register and medium register. However, in the medium register, {{IPA|/y, yÀê/}} and {{IPA|/≈ì, ≈ìÀê/}} are often either too back, which results in realizations that are phonetically too close to, respectively, {{IPA|/u, uÀê/}} and {{IPA|/…î, …îÀê/}}, or too weakly rounded, yielding vowels that are phonetically too close to, respectively, {{IPA|/i, iÀê/}} and {{IPA|/…õ, …õÀê/}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=57, 64‚Äì65, 103}}
* {{IPA|/uÀê, …õÀê/}} do not occur after soft consonants, where they are replaced by the corresponding diphthongs {{IPA|/…™ÃØu, …™ÃØ…õ/}}. The same is generally true for {{IPA|/aÀê/}} ({{IPA|/…™ÃØa/}} after soft consonants), but the sequence {{IPA|/jaÀê/}} may occur in some cases.{{sfnp|Short|2002|pp=534‚Äì535}}
* Long {{IPA|/…õÀê/}} occurs only in loanwords, one native word (''dc√©ra'') and in adjective endings.{{sfnp|Short|2002|p=535}}
* {{IPA|/√¶/}} can only be short, and occurs only after {{IPA|/m, p, b, v/}}.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=375}}{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=55}} There is not a full agreement about its status in the standard language:
** {{Harvcoltxt|Kr√°ƒæ|1988}} states that the correct pronunciation of {{IPA|/√¶/}} is an important part of the high register, but in medium and low registers, {{IPA|/√¶/}} merges with {{IPA|/…õ/}}, or, in some cases, with {{IPA|/a/}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=55}}
** {{Harvcoltxt|Short|2002}} states that only about 5% of speakers have {{IPA|/√¶/}} as a distinct phoneme, and that even when it is used in formal contexts, it is most often a dialect feature.{{sfnp|Short|2002|p=534}}
** {{Harvcoltxt|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010}} state that the use of {{IPA|/√¶/}} is becoming rare, and that it often merges with {{IPA|/…õ/}}.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=375}}

