* Voiceless stops and affricates are unaspirated.
* Voiced stops and affricates are fully voiced.
* {{IPA|/n/}} is [[Apical consonant|apical]] alveolar {{IPAblink|n|nÃ∫}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=73}}. The author describes {{IPA|/n/}} as apical alveolar, but the corresponding image shows a laminal denti-alveolar pronunciation (which he does not discuss).</ref>
* {{IPA|/t, d, tÕ°s, dÕ°z, s, z, …≤, c, …ü/}} are laminal {{IPA|[tÃª, dÃª, tÃªÕ°sÃª, dÃªÕ°zÃª, sÃª, zÃª, …≤Ãª, cÃª, …üÃª]}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=72, 74‚Äì75, 80‚Äì82}}
** {{IPA|/t, d/}} are alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t}}, {{IPA link|d}}]}} or denti-alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|tÃ™}}, {{IPA link|dÃ™}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=72}}{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|pp=98‚Äì99}}
** {{IPA|/tÕ°s, dÕ°z, s, z/}} are alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|tÕ°s}}, {{IPA link|dÕ°z}}, {{IPA link|s}}, {{IPA link|z}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=74‚Äì75}}{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|pp=103‚Äì104}}
*** Word-initial {{IPA|/dÕ°z/}} occurs only in two words: ''dzeka≈•'' and ''dziny''.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
** {{IPA|/c, …ü, …≤/}} are [[Alveolo-palatal consonant|alveolo-palatal]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|c|cÃü<sup>√ß</sup>}}, {{IPA link|…ü|…üÃü<sup> ù</sup>}}, {{IPA link|…≤Ãü}}]}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Dvonƒçov√°|Jenƒça|Kr√°ƒæ|1969|pp=?}}, cited in {{Harvcoltxt|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}</ref>{{sfnp|Pauliny|1979|p=112}}{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=81‚Äì82}}{{sfnp|Recasens|2013|pp=11, 13}}
*** As indicated in the transcription, {{IPA|/c, …ü/}} are weakly affricated.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=80}}
*** {{IPA|/…≤/}} can also be dento-alveolo-palatal.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=81‚Äì82}}
* {{IPA|/ é/}} is palatalized laminal denti-alveolar {{IPAblink| é|lÃ™ ≤}},{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=82}} palatalized laminal alveolar {{IPAblink| é|lÃª ≤}}{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=82}}{{sfnp|Dvonƒçov√°|Jenƒça|Kr√°ƒæ|1969|pp=94‚Äì95}} or palatal {{IPAblink| é}}.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=82}}{{sfnp|Dvonƒçov√°|Jenƒça|Kr√°ƒæ|1969|pp=94‚Äì95}} The palatal realization is the least common one.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}{{sfnp|Dvonƒçov√°|Jenƒça|Kr√°ƒæ|1969|pp=94‚Äì95}}
** {{Harvcoltxt|Pavl√≠k|2004}} describes an additional realization, namely a weakly palatalized apical alveolar approximant {{IPA|[lÃ∫ ≤]}}. According to this scholar, the palatal realization {{IPA|[ é]}} is actually alveolo-palatal {{IPAblink| éÃü}}.{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|p=105}}
* The {{IPA|/ é‚Äìl/}} contrast is neutralized before front vowels, where only {{IPA|/l/}} occurs. This neutralization is taken further in western dialects, in which {{IPA|/ é/}} merges with {{IPA|/l/}} in all environments.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
* {{IPA|/l, r/}} are apical alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|l|lÃ∫}}, {{IPA link|r|rÃ∫}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|pp=78‚Äì79}}
** {{IPA|/l/}} is either neutral {{IPAblink|l}} or velarized {{IPAblink|…´}}.{{sfnp|Kr√°ƒæ|1988|p=80}}
** Short {{IPA|/r/}} is most often a tap {{IPAblink|…æ}}.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
* Postalveolar {{IPA|/tÕ° É, dÕ° í,  É,  í/}} are often pronounced hard, i.e. as laminal retroflex (flat postalveolar) {{IPA|[{{IPA link|tÕ° Ç}}, {{IPA link|dÕ° ê}}, {{IPA link| Ç}}, {{IPA link| ê}}]}},{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}} as in [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Polish language|Polish]].
** {{IPA|/dÕ° í/}} occurs mainly in loanwords.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
* {{IPA|/v/}} is realized as:
** Voiced fricative {{IPAblink|v}} in onsets before voiced obstruents;{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
** Voiceless fricative {{IPAblink|f}} in onsets before voiceless obstruents;{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|pp=374, 376}}
** Variably as an approximant {{IPAblink| ã}} or a glide {{IPA|[ äÃØ]}} in [[Syllable#Coda|coda]];{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
** Approximant {{IPAblink| ã}} in all other cases.{{sfnp|Hanul√≠kov√°|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
* {{IPA|/j/}} is an approximant, either palatal or alveolo-palatal.{{sfnp|Recasens|2013|p=15}} Between close front vowels, it can be realized as a fricative {{IPAblink| ù}}, whereas between open central vowels, it can be a quite lax approximant {{IPA|[jÀï]}}.{{sfnp|Pavl√≠k|2004|p=106}}

Some additional notes includes the following (transcriptions in IPA unless otherwise stated):
* {{IPA|/r, l/}} can be syllabic: {{IPA|/rÃ©, lÃ©/}}. When they are long (indicated in the spelling with the acute accent: '''≈ï''' and '''ƒ∫'''), they are always syllabic, e.g. ''vlk'' (wolf), ''prst'' (finger), ''≈°tvr≈•'' (quarter), ''krk'' (neck), bisyllabic ''vƒ∫ƒça''‚Äî''vƒ∫-ƒça'' (wolfling), ''v≈ïba''‚Äî''v≈ï-ba'' (willow-tree), etc.
* {{IPA|/m/}} has the allophone {{IPA|[…±]}} in front of the labiodental fricatives {{IPA|/f/}} and {{IPA|/v/}}.
* {{IPA|/n/}} in front of (post)alveolar fricatives has a postalveolar allophone {{IPA|[nÃ†]}}.
* {{IPA|/n/}} can be {{IPA|[≈ã]}} in front of the velar plosives {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/…°/}}.

==Stress==
{{unreferenced section|date=April 2015}}
In the standard language, the [[stress (linguistics)|stress]] is always on the first syllable of a word (or on the preceding preposition, see below). This is not the case in certain dialects. Eastern dialects have penultimate stress (as in [[Polish phonology|Polish]]), which at times makes them difficult to understand for speakers of standard Slovak. Some of the north-central dialects have a weak stress on the first syllable, which becomes stronger and moves to the penultimate in certain cases. Monosyllabic conjunctions, monosyllabic short personal pronouns and auxiliary verb forms of the verb ''by≈•'' (to be) are usually unstressed.

[[Preposition]]s form a single [[Prosody (linguistics)|prosodic]] unit with the following word, unless the word is long (four syllables or more) or the preposition stands at the beginning of a sentence.

==Official transcriptions==
{{unreferenced section|date=April 2015}}
Slovak linguists do not usually use IPA for phonetic transcription of their own language or others, but have their own system based on the Slovak alphabet. Many English language textbooks make use of this  alternative transcription system.
In the following table, pronunciation of each grapheme is given in this system as well as in the IPA.

