{{Language phonologies}}

{{DEFAULTSORT:Slovak Phonology}}
[[Category:Slovak language|Phonology]]
[[Category:Language phonologies]]

{{Infobox language |name=Waziristani |altname=Waziri, Dawari, Maseedwola |states=[[Pakistan]], [[Afghanistan]] |region=[[Waziristan]] |speakers= |date= |ref= |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] |fam3=[[Iranian languages|Iranian]] |fam4=[[Eastern Iranian languages|Eastern]] |fam5 = [[Pashto dialects|Pashto]] |script= |iso3=none |isoexception = dialect |glotto=waci1238 |glottorefname=Waziri }}
'''Waziristani''' ({{lang-ps|Ÿàÿ≤€åÿ±ÿ≥ÿ™ÿßŸÜ€ç}}), also known as '''Wazirwola''' ({{lang-ps|Ÿàÿ≤€åÿ±ŸàÿßŸÑŸá}}, meaning "of the [[Wazir (Pashtun tribe)|Wazirs]]"), '''Waziri''', '''Dawari''', or '''Maseedwola''', is an east-central [[Pashto dialect]] spoken in [[North Waziristan]], [[South Waziristan]], and parts of [[Bannu District|Bannu]] and [[Tank District|Tank]] in [[Pakistan]], and in certain adjacent districts of [[Paktika Province|Paktika]], [[Khost Province|Khost]] and [[Paktia Province|Paktia]] provinces of [[Afghanistan]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
The Waziristani dialect is almost identical to the dialect spoken around [[Urgun]] (eastern [[Paktika province]]) and the Bannuchi dialect of [[Bannu]], and somewhat resembles the dialect spoken by [[Khattak]]s in [[Karak, Pakistan|Karak]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} The dialects of [[Loya Paktia]] like Zadrani are also very closely related, except that they are of the harsh northern variety.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
Waziristani differs significantly in pronunciation and grammar from the standard literary Pashto based on the larger [[Kandahar]], [[Kabul]] and [[Yousafzai]] dialects.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} The vowels [a], […ë], [u] and [o] of standard Pashto yield […ë], [o], [i] and [e] respectively, so [pa Çto] becomes [p…ë…ïte] in Waziristani.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} A special feature of Waziristani is that the phonemes [ É] and [ Ç], along with their voiced counterparts, [ í] and [ ê], have merged into the phonemes […ï] and [ ë],{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} both of which also exist in the nearby [[Ormuri]] language of [[Kaniguram]], South Waziristan.<ref>Rozi Khan Burki. [http://www.khyber.org/publications/016-020/ormuri.shtml "Dying Languages; Special Focus on Ormuri"]. Originally published in ''Pakistan Journal of Public Administration; Volume 6. No. 2'' in December 2001. ''Khyber.ORG''.</ref> The [[Pashto alphabet]] has no symbol for their expression and the regular symbols of ⁄ò and ÿ¥ may be used.
The standard Pashto word for "boy", "ŸáŸÑ⁄©" [hal…ôk], is rarely heard in Waziristani, instead, "Ÿà€ê⁄ì⁄©€å" [we…ªkai] meaning "little one" is used. The word "l…ôshki" [l…ô…ïki] is used instead of the standard "ŸÑ⁄ñ" [l…ô ê], "a little bit". The pronoun ŸÖŸà⁄ñ ([mu ê] or [mung]), meaning "we", is pronounced [mi ë] in Waziristani.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
Waziristani, like many other obscure Pashto dialects, is almost never written and its speakers may use standard Pashto as a literary language. Waziristani Pashto is spoken by various tribes, and it is also called ''Maseedwola'' by the [[Mahsuds]] and ''Dawarwola'' by the [[Dawari]]. There are slight differences in pronunciation, for example, the phonemes [tÕ°s] and [dÕ°z] can become [s] and [z], or even [tÕ° É] and [dÕ° í], depending on the tribe or area the speaker is from.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
